Step 4: Transition

If we don't take current element

dp[i][j]
=
dp[i-1][j]

If we take it

dp[i-1][j-nums[i-1]]

Tabulation Code
class Solution {
public:
    bool canPartition(vector<int>& nums) {

        int sum = 0;

        for(int x: nums)
            sum += x;

        if(sum % 2)
            return false;

        int target = sum / 2;
        int n = nums.size();

        vector<vector<bool>> dp(n + 1,
                                vector<bool>(target + 1, false));

        for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++)
            dp[i][0] = true;

        for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {

            for(int j = 1; j <= target; j++) {

                if(nums[i-1] <= j)
                    dp[i][j] =
                        dp[i-1][j] ||
                        dp[i-1][j-nums[i-1]];
                else
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j];
            }
        }

        return dp[n][target];
    }
};

Time:

O(n * target)

Space:

O(n * target)




Space Optimization (Interview Favourite ⭐⭐⭐)

Notice every row only depends on the previous row.

So use one array.

Important Trick

Traverse backwards.

for each number

    for(j = target → num)

Why backwards?

Because this is 0/1 Knapsack.

Each element can only be used once.

If we went forward, we'd accidentally reuse the same number multiple times.

Optimized Code
class Solution {
public:
    bool canPartition(vector<int>& nums) {

        int sum = 0;

        for(int x : nums)
            sum += x;

        if(sum % 2)
            return false;

        int target = sum / 2;

        vector<bool> dp(target + 1, false);

        dp[0] = true;

        for(int num : nums) {

            for(int j = target; j >= num; j--) {

                dp[j] = dp[j] || dp[j - num];
            }
        }

        return dp[target];
    }
};

Time:

O(n × target)

Space:

O(target)
